04549nam a22007095i 9780814759301DE-B159720200608045044.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200608t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011028197  a97808147593017 a10.18574/97808147593012doi  a(DE-B1597)548319  a(OCoLC)774293615  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE185.615b.N86 2016 7aPOL0080002bisacsh04a305.8960732231 aNunnally, Shayla C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTrust in Black America :bRace, Discrimination, and Politics /cShayla C. Nunnally. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Explaining Blacks' (Dis)trust -- t3. Being Black in America -- t4. Trust No One -- t5. Trusting Bodies, Racing Trust -- t6. The Societal Context -- t7. The Political Context -- t8. Conclusion -- tAppendix A -- tAppendix B -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe more citizens trust their government, the better democracy functions. However, African Americans have long suffered from the lack of equal protection by their government, and the racial discrimination they have faced breaks down their trust in democracy. Rather than promoting democracy, the United States government has, from its inception, racially discriminated against African American citizens and other racial groups, denying them equal access to citizenship and to protection of the law. Civil rights violations by ordinary citizens have also tainted social relationships between racial groups-social relationships that should be meaningful for enhancing relations between citizens and the government at large. Thus, trust and democracy do not function in American politics the way they should, in part because trust is not color blind. Based on the premise that racial discrimination breaks down trust in a democracy, Trust in Black America examines the effect of race on African Americans' lives. Shayla Nunnally analyzes public opinion data from two national surveys to provide an updated and contemporary analysis of African Americans' political socialization, and to explore how African Americans learn about race. She argues that the uncertainty, risk, and unfairness of institutionalized racial discrimination has led African Americans to have a fundamentally different understanding of American race relations, so much so that distrust has been the basis for which race relations have been understood by African Americans. Nunnally empirically demonstrates that race and racial discrimination have broken down trust in American democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxAttitudes. 0aAfrican AmericansxPsychology. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocialization. 0aPolitical socializationzUnited States. 0aTrustxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aTrustxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814759301.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK